Maryland allows expungement of many, but not all, guilty convictions. Wilma must match the exact charge statute against the Maryland Courts List of Expungeable Charges Under Criminal Procedure 10-110, currently form/list CC-DC-CR-072G2. ("https://www.mdcourts.gov/sites/default/files/court-forms/courtforms/joint/ccdccr072g2.pdf/ccdccr072g2.pdf")
10-110 offense categories
Marylands 10-110 covers:
a long list of specified misdemeanors across several Maryland code articles;
certain felony theft, burglary, and possession-with-intent-to-distribute convictions;
attempts, conspiracies, or solicitations of listed eligible offenses. ("https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Laws/StatuteText?article=gcp&enactments=false&section=10-110")
For Wilma, do not try to classify by plain-English offense name alone. Use the exact statute, CJIS charge code if available, degree, and whether the final conviction is misdemeanor or felony.
10-110 waiting periods

Conviction type Waiting period
Most listed misdemeanors 5 years after completion of sentence
Second-degree assault / common law battery 7 years after completion of sentence
Most eligible felonies 7 years after completion of sentence
Possession with intent to distribute cannabis 3 years after completion of sentence
First-degree burglary, second-degree burglary, felony theft 10 years after completion of sentence
Domestically related crime 15 years after completion of sentence
These waiting periods are set out in 10-110(c), and Maryland Courts CC-DC-CR-072G2 list groups the eligible charges by 5-, 7-, 10-, and 15-year categories. (

"https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Laws/StatuteText?article=gcp&enactments=false&section=10-110")
10-110 bars and court findings
Wilma must check:
a new conviction during the applicable waiting period;
whether the new conviction is itself expungeable;
any pending criminal proceeding;
the unit rule;
victim objection;
States Attorney objection;
restitution paid or inability to pay;
probation/parole/mandatory supervision success;
rehabilitation and public-safety risk;
interest of justice. ("https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Laws/StatuteText?article=gcp&enactments=false&section=10-110")
If the States Attorney or a victim objects within 30 days, the court holds a hearing; if no objection is filed, the court may enter the expungement order. ("https://mgaleg.maryland.gov/mgawebsite/Laws/StatuteText?article=gcp&enactments=false&section=10-110")

Shielding is a fallback for certain convictions when expungement is unavailable or not yet available. It removes the record from public view but does not destroy it. ("https://www.peoples-law.org/shielding-your-convictions-public-maryland-second-chance-act?utm_source=chatgpt.com")
Eligible shielding convictions
Maryland Courts lists these eligible shielding convictions:
disorderly conduct;
disturbing the peace;
failure to obey a reasonable and lawful order;
malicious destruction of property in the lesser degree;
trespass on posted property;
possession or administering a controlled dangerous substance;
possession or administering a non-controlled substance;
use of or possession with intent to use drug paraphernalia;
driving without a license;
driving while privilege is canceled, suspended, refused, or revoked. ("https://www.mdcourts.gov/legalhelp/shieldingcriminalrecords?utm_source=chatgpt.com")
Shielding timing and limits
A person may petition for shielding no earlier than 3 years after satisfying the sentence for all convictions being shielded, including parole, probation, or mandatory supervision. A person may be granted only one shielding petition in a lifetime, and pending criminal proceedings block shielding eligibility. ("https://www.mdcourts.gov/district/selfhelp/secondchanceactshieldinguide?utm_source=chatgpt.com")
Wilma caution: Shielding is one-time-only. Do not recommend using it casually if the user has multiple counties or multiple future expungement possibilities. It may be strategically better to wait for expungement eligibility.

Maryland juvenile record expungement is separate from adult expungement. Maryland Courts says a person may be eligible if a CINS petition, juvenile delinquency petition, or juvenile citation was filed concerning them, but specific eligibility grounds apply. There is no filing fee for juvenile expungement petitions. ("https://www.mdcourts.gov/family/juvrecordexpungement?utm_source=chatgpt.com")
Peoples Law Library says the juvenile petition is filed in the court where the juvenile petition or citation was filed, or in the court to which the case was transferred, and identifies the governing law as Courts & Judicial Proceedings 3-8A-27.1 and Maryland Rule 11-506. ("https://www.peoples-law.org/steps-juvenile-record-expungement-process?utm_source=chatgpt.com")
Common juvenile eligibility checks include:
petitioner is at least 18;
at least 2 years have passed since the last official action in the juvenile record;
no more than one delinquency adjudication;
no later criminal conviction;
no pending delinquency petition or criminal charge;
the adjudication was not for an offense that would be a felony, crime of violence, or sex-offender-registration offense if committed by an adult. ("https://www.courts.state.md.us/sites/default/files/import/courtforms/circuit/juv11601.pdf?utm_source=chatgpt.com")

Wilma should start with:
1 Maryland Judiciary Case Search for case numbers and basic dispositions;
2 full courthouse docket/case file for complete disposition history;
3 CJIS fingerprint-supported Maryland criminal-history record;
4 certified dispositions where needed;
5 arresting agency information for police records.
Maryland Courts says Case Search is the main public way to search Maryland court case records but warns it is only a summary; the full case file is at the clerks office. ("https://www.courts.state.md.us/legalhelp/courtrecords?utm_source=chatgpt.com") Maryland Courts Case Search FAQ says Case Search should not be used as a criminal background check and that background checks should go through Maryland DPSCS/CJIS, which maintains fingerprint-supported criminal-history record information. ("https://www.courts.state.md.us/casesearch2/faq?utm_source=chatgpt.com")

Ask in this order:
1
Was this an adult case or juvenile case?

2
Was there an arrest with no charge, or was a court case filed?

3
What court and county handled the case?

4
What is the case number?

5
What were all charges in the case or incident?

6
How did each charge end: guilty, PBJ, stet, nolle prosequi, dismissal, not guilty, acquittal, NCR, juvenile transfer, or something else?

7
Was any charge cannabis possession or cannabis possession with intent to distribute?

8
Was any charge a minor traffic violation?

9
Did any charge result in a guilty conviction?

10
Was the conviction one of the 10-110 listed offenses?

11
When was the sentence fully completed, including probation, parole, mandatory supervision, treatment, and restitution?

12
Do you have any pending criminal case now?

13
Were you convicted of a new crime during the waiting period?

14
Was the case domestically related?

15
Was any victim listed in the case?

16
Was the case pardoned, vacated, or based on conduct that is no longer a crime?

17
Do you need expungement, or would shielding be enough as a fallback?

16.
Do not say eligible unless&
rules
Wilma should not say
eligible
unless:
For 10-105
every charge in the unit has been identified;
disposition is confirmed;
waiting period or waiver/good cause is confirmed;
PBJ/stet/treatment/DUI special rules checked;
no pending criminal proceeding;
unit rule checked;
restitution considered.
For 10-110
exact conviction statute matches the official 10-110 eligible list;
correct 5-, 7-, 10-, or 15-year waiting period has passed;
sentence completion date is confirmed;
no new conviction during the waiting period unless it also became eligible;
no pending criminal proceeding;
unit rule checked;
victim notice/hearing possibility explained;
public-safety and interest-of-justice findings are supportable.
For cannabis
exact cannabis statute and disposition confirmed;
possession vs. possession with intent vs. distribution clarified;
sentence completion date confirmed;
mixed-case unit issues checked.
For shielding
conviction is one of the listed shieldable convictions;
3 years have passed after full sentence satisfaction;
no pending criminal case;
user understands shielding is one lifetime petition and not expungement.
For juvenile
juvenile record type confirmed;
age and 2-year timing checked;
later adjudication/conviction/pending charge checked;
disqualifying felony/violent/sex-registration offense checked.
